  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Multi-sectoral emergency support to conflict affected population in Hassakeh, Deraa and Rural Damascus</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Syrian Arab Republic is now in its sixth year of civil conflict, whereby a political solution remains elusive. 6.5 million People have been displaced within Syria, putting under further pressure exhausted host communities and collapsing infrastructures. 4.5 million People are living in hard to reach areas where they experience protracted isolation and very poor conditions. Syria requires both effective humanitarian assistance to meet the immediate survival needs of the most vulnerable groups in besieged/hard to reach areas, and sustainable solutions for displaced people and host communities.
Against this background, building on ACF previous experiences, the proposed intervention will focus on three key sectors of humanitarian intervention &#x2013; WASH, NFIs and Livelihoods &#x2013; providing integrated multi-sectorial assistance to estimated 350,000 individuals in Daraa, Rural Damascus and Hassakeh Governorates, with special attention to hard-to-reach areas. In particular, the initiative will complement short-term life-saving assistance (winter cloths, and water trucking) with longer-term solutions to protect or restore livelihood assets (maintenance/rehabilitation of water systems, provision of home gardening kits for vegetables production, and capacity building to beneficiaries to maximize the assistance received). Due to the integrated needs, ACF will ensure a comprehensive approach, targeting the same locations and beneficiaries within the three component of the project (WASH, NFIs, and Livelihoods). A set of activities have been purposely designed to meet the needs of specific vulnerable categories: winter cloths distribution, in particular cotton underwear, sport cloths and pajamas for children (boys and girls) 2-12 years of age, while home gardening activities will mainly target women according to traditional gender roles and opportunities. When possible, selection criteria of beneficiaries will consider both PWD and elders, while project monitoring and evaluation will ensure gender impact and collection of disaggregated data. As well, the proposed intervention mainstreams and incorporates protection principles in all activities to promote meaningful access, safety and dignity. ACF will ensure direct implementation of activities through the regular presence of its staff in the field, while promoting synergies and collaboration with project partners, namely the Ministry of Water Resources (MoWR), Ministry of Agriculture and Agrarian Reforms (MAAR), Arab Center for Studies of Arid lands and Dry zones (ACSAD) and Syrian Arab Red Crescent (SARC) with whom ACF boats long lasting partnerships set forth by the signature by specific MoUs.</narrative>
  </description>
